# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hsts-preload
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] An example of such a flaw was found in OpenSSL that allowed the attacker to negotiate the use of a lower version of TLS between the client and server.
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] This is one of the most common types of downgrade attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] Opportunistic encryption protocols such as STARTTLS are generally vulnerable to downgrade attacks, as they, by design, fall back to unencrypted communication.
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] Websites which rely on redirects from unencrypted HTTP to encrypted HTTPS can also be vulnerable to downgrade attacks (e.g., sslstrip), as the initial redirect is not protected by encryption.
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] Downgrade attacks are often implemented as part of a man-in-the-middle (MITM) attack, and may be used as a way of enabling a cryptographic attack that might not be possible otherwise.
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] Downgrade attacks have been a consistent problem with the SSL/TLS family of protocols; examples of such attacks include the POODLE attack.
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] Downgrade attacks in the TLS protocol take many forms.
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] Removing backward compatibility is often the only way to prevent downgrade attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/downgrade-attack] However, sometimes the client and server can recognize each other as up-to-date in a manner that prevents them.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] Since sites tell the browser that they support HSTS when the browser visits, the browser cannot know a site's HSTS policy before the user has visited the site for the first time.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] As a result, the browser can not require HTTPS until after the first time it has connected to the site, possibly leaving the user unprotected.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] After this first load, the web browser has the site's HSTS policy and is able to require HTTPS for all subsequent loads.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] To account for this first-load problem, Chrome maintains a list of domains that have a strong HSTS policy and are HTTPS only.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] This HSTS preload list is built into Chrome.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] Requests to these domains will only be made over HTTPS; any HTTP requests will be upgraded to HTTPS and fail to connect if HTTPS is unavailable.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] Other major browsers (Firefox, Safari, IE 11 and Edge) also have HSTS preload lists based on the Chrome list.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] Many browsers (Chrome, Safari) will automatically upgrade all HTTP navigations to HTTPS, regardless of the domain's HSTS policy.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] HSTS preloading only provides value when these upgrades fail in the presence of an active attacker.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] The benefits provided by HSTS preloading are minimal compared to the benefits provided by HSTS.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] While HSTS is recommended, **HSTS *preloading* is not recommended**.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] If a site sends the `preload` directive in an HSTS header, it is considered to be requesting inclusion in the preload list and may be submitted via the form on this site.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] **Redirect** from HTTP to HTTPS on the same host, if you are listening on port 80.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] For more details on HSTS, please see RFC 6797.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] You can check the status of your request by entering the domain name again in the form above, or consult the current Chrome preload list by visiting `chrome://net-internals/#hsts` in your browser.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] Note that new entries are hardcoded into the Chrome source code and can take several months before they reach the stable version.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] You must make sure your site continues to satisfy the submission requirements at all times.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] Note that removing the `preload` directive from your header will make your site immediately eligible for the removal form, and that sites may be removed automatically in the future for failing to keep up the requirements.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] The same requirements apply to earlier domains submitted on or after **February 29, 2016** (i.e. preloaded after Chrome 50), except that the required max-age for those domains is only `10886400` seconds.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] If you maintain a project that provides HTTPS configuration advice or provides an option to enable HSTS, **do not include the `preload` directive by default**.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] We get regular emails from site operators who tried out HSTS this way, only to find themselves on the preload list without realizing that some subdomains cannot support HTTPS.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] Removal tends to be slow and painful for those sites.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] Projects that support or advise about HSTS and HSTS preloading should ensure that site operators understand the long-term consequences of preloading before they turn it on for a given domain.
[src:hsts-preload/hstspreload-org] They should also be informed that they need to meet additional requirements and submit their site to hstspreload.org to ensure that it is successfully preloaded (i.e. to get the full protection of the intended configuration).
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS Policy is communicated by the server to the user agent via an HTTP response header field named `Strict-Transport-Security`.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS Policy specifies a period of time during which the user agent should only access the server in a secure fashion.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Websites using HSTS often do not accept clear text HTTP, either by rejecting connections over HTTP or systematically redirecting users to HTTPS (though this is not required by the specification).
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The consequence of this is that a user-agent not capable of doing TLS will not be able to connect to the site.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The protection normally only applies after a user has visited the site at least once, relying on the principle of "trust on first use".
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The way this protection works is that when a user entering or selecting an HTTP (not HTTPS) URL to the site, the client, such as a Web browser, will automatically upgrade to HTTPS without making an HTTP request, thereby preventing any HTTP man-in-the-middle attack from occurring.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] To counteract this problem, an HSTS preload list maintained by Google Chrome and used by other major web browsers is maintained.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] If a domain is on this list, the browser skips the initial request and encrypts all communication immediately.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Additional domains can be registered at no cost.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS specification was published as RFC 6797 on 19 November 2012 after being approved on 2 October 2012 by the IESG for publication as a Proposed Standard RFC.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The authors originally submitted it as an Internet Draft on 17 June 2010.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] With the conversion to an Internet Draft, the specification name was altered from "Strict Transport Security" (STS) to "HTTP Strict Transport Security", because the specification applies only to HTTP.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The HTTP response header field defined in the HSTS specification however remains named "Strict-Transport-Security".
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The last so-called "community version" of the then-named "STS" specification was published on 18 December 2009, with revisions based on community feedback.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The original draft specification by Jeff Hodges from PayPal, Collin Jackson, and Adam Barth was published on 18 September 2009.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS specification is based on original work by Jackson and Barth as described in their paper "ForceHTTPS: Protecting High-Security Web Sites from Network Attacks".
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Additionally, HSTS is the realization of one facet of an overall vision for improving web security, put forward by Jeff Hodges and Andy Steingruebl in their 2010 paper *The Need for Coherent Web Security Policy Framework(s)*.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] A server implements an HSTS policy by supplying a header over an HTTPS connection (HSTS headers over HTTP are ignored).
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] For example, a server could send a header such that future requests to the domain for the next year (max-age is specified in seconds; 31,536,000 is equal to one non-leap year) use only HTTPS: `Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000`.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] If the security of the connection cannot be ensured (e.g. the server's TLS certificate is not trusted), the user agent must terminate the connection and should not allow the user to access the web application.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] This helps protect web application users against some passive (eavesdropping) and active network attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] A man-in-the-middle attacker has a greatly reduced ability to intercept requests and responses between a user and a web application server while the user's browser has HSTS Policy in effect for that web application.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The most important security vulnerability that HSTS can fix is SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, first publicly introduced by Moxie Marlinspike in his 2009 BlackHat Federal talk "New Tricks For Defeating SSL In Practice".
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The SSL (and TLS) stripping attack works by transparently converting a secure HTTPS connection into a plain HTTP connection.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The user can see that the connection is insecure, but crucially there is no way of knowing whether the connection *should* be secure.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] At the time of Marlinspike's talk, many websites did not use TLS/SSL, therefore there was no way of knowing (without prior knowledge) whether the use of plain HTTP was due to an attack, or simply because the website had not implemented TLS/SSL.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Additionally, no warnings are presented to the user during the downgrade process, making the attack fairly subtle to all but the most vigilant.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Marlinspike's sslstrip tool, presented at Black Hat DC 2009, fully automates the attack.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS addresses this problem by informing the browser that connections to the site should always use TLS/SSL.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS header can be stripped by the attacker if this is the user's first visit.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Microsoft Edge attempt to limit this problem by including a "pre-loaded" list of HSTS sites.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Unfortunately this solution cannot scale to include all websites on the internet.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS can also help to prevent having one's cookie-based website login credentials stolen by widely available tools such as Firesheep.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Because HSTS is time limited, it is sensitive to attacks involving shifting the victim's computer time e.g. using false NTP packets.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The initial request remains unprotected from active attacks if it uses an insecure protocol such as plain HTTP or if the URI for the initial request was obtained over an insecure channel.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] The same applies to the first request after the activity period specified in the advertised HSTS Policy `max-age` (sites should set a period of several days or months depending on user activity and behavior).
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, and Internet Explorer/Microsoft Edge address this limitation by implementing a "HSTS preloaded list", which is a list that contains known sites supporting HSTS.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] This list is distributed with the browser so that it uses HTTPS for the initial request to the listed sites as well.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] As previously mentioned, these pre-loaded lists cannot scale to cover the entire Web.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] A potential solution might be achieved by using DNS records to declare HSTS Policy, and accessing them securely via DNSSEC, optionally with certificate fingerprints to ensure validity (which requires running a validating resolver to avoid last mile issues).
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Even with an HSTS preloaded list, HSTS cannot prevent advanced attacks against TLS itself, such as the BEAST or CRIME attacks introduced by Juliano Rizzo and Thai Duong.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Attacks against TLS itself are orthogonal to HSTS policy enforcement.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Neither can it protect against attacks on the server - if someone compromises it, it will happily serve any content over TLS.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS can be used to near-indelibly tag visiting browsers with recoverable identifying data (supercookies) which can persist in and out of browser "incognito" privacy modes.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] By creating a web page that makes multiple HTTP requests to selected domains, for example, if twenty browser requests to twenty different domains are used, theoretically over one million visitors can be distinguished (220) due to the resulting requests arriving via HTTP vs.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] HTTPS; the latter being the previously recorded binary "bits" established earlier via HSTS headers.
[src:hsts-preload/http-strict-transport-security] Depending on the actual deployment there are certain threats (e.g. cookie injection attacks) that can be avoided by following best practices.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The principal motivations for HTTPS are authentication of the accessed website and protection of the privacy and integrity of the exchanged data while it is in transit.
[src:hsts-preload/https] It protects against man-in-the-middle attacks, and the bidirectional block cipher encryption of communications between a client and server protects the communications against eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The authentication aspect of HTTPS requires a trusted third party to sign server-side digital certificates.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This was historically an expensive operation, which meant fully authenticated HTTPS connections were usually found only on secured payment transaction services and other secured corporate information systems on the World Wide Web.
[src:hsts-preload/https] In 2016, a campaign by the Electronic Frontier Foundation with the support of web browser developers led to the protocol becoming more prevalent.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS has since 2018 been used more often by web users than non-secure HTTP, primarily to protect page authenticity on all types of websites, secure accounts, and keep user communications, identity, and web browsing private.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) scheme *HTTPS* has identical usage syntax to the HTTP scheme.
[src:hsts-preload/https] However, HTTPS signals the browser to use an added encryption layer of SSL/TLS to protect the traffic.
[src:hsts-preload/https] SSL/TLS is especially suited for HTTP, since it can provide some protection even if only one side of the communication is authenticated.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This is the case with HTTP transactions over the Internet, where typically only the server is authenticated (by the client examining the server's certificate).
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS creates a secure channel over an insecure network.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This ensures reasonable protection from eavesdroppers and man-in-the-middle attacks, provided that adequate cipher suites are used and that the server certificate is verified and trusted.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Because HTTPS piggybacks HTTP entirely on top of TLS, the entirety of the underlying HTTP protocol can be encrypted.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This includes the request's URL, query parameters, headers, and cookies (which often contain identifying information about the user).
[src:hsts-preload/https] However, because website addresses and port numbers are necessarily part of the underlying TCP/IP protocols, HTTPS cannot protect their disclosure.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Web browsers know how to trust HTTPS websites based on certificate authorities that come pre-installed in their software.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Certificate authorities are in this way being trusted by web browser creators to provide valid certificates.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS is especially important over insecure networks and networks that may be subject to tampering.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Insecure networks, such as public Wi-Fi access points, allow anyone on the same local network to packet-sniff and discover sensitive information not protected by HTTPS.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Additionally, some free-to-use and paid WLAN networks have been observed tampering with webpages by engaging in packet injection in order to serve their own ads on other websites.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This practice can be exploited maliciously in many ways, such as by injecting malware onto webpages and stealing users' private information.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS is also important for connections over the Tor network, as malicious Tor nodes could otherwise damage or alter the contents passing through them in an insecure fashion and inject malware into the connection.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This is one reason why the Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Tor Project started the development of HTTPS Everywhere, which is included in Tor Browser.
[src:hsts-preload/https] As more information is revealed about global mass surveillance and criminals stealing personal information, the use of HTTPS security on all websites is becoming increasingly important regardless of the type of Internet connection being used.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Even though metadata about individual pages that a user visits might not be considered sensitive, when aggregated it can reveal a lot about the user and compromise the user's privacy.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Deploying HTTPS also allows the use of HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 (and their predecessors SPDY and QUIC), which are new HTTP versions designed to reduce page load times, size, and latency.
[src:hsts-preload/https] It is recommended to use HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) with HTTPS to protect users from man-in-the-middle attacks, especially SSL stripping.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS should not be confused with the seldom-used Secure HTTP (S-HTTP) specified in RFC 2660.
[src:hsts-preload/https] As of April 2018, 33.2% of Alexa top 1,000,000 websites use HTTPS as default and 70% of page loads (measured by Firefox Telemetry) use HTTPS.
[src:hsts-preload/https] As of June 2025, 71.2% of the Internet's 150,000 most popular websites have a secure implementation of HTTPS (up from 58.4% in December 2022), However, despite TLS 1.3's release in 2018, adoption has been slow, with many still remaining on the older TLS 1.2 protocol.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Most browsers display a warning if they receive an invalid certificate.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Older browsers, when connecting to a site with an invalid certificate, would present the user with a dialog box asking whether they wanted to continue.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Newer browsers display a warning across the entire window.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Newer browsers also prominently display the site's security information in the address bar.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Extended validation certificates show the legal entity on the certificate information.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Most browsers also display a warning to the user when visiting a site that contains a mixture of encrypted and unencrypted content.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Additionally, many web filters return a security warning when visiting prohibited websites.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, opining that "In an ideal world, every web request could be defaulted to HTTPS", has provided an add-on called HTTPS Everywhere for Mozilla Firefox, Google Chrome, Chromium, and Android, which enables HTTPS by default for hundreds of frequently used websites.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Forcing a web browser to load only HTTPS content has been supported in Firefox starting in version 83.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Starting in version 94, Google Chrome is able to "always use secure connections" if toggled in the browser's settings.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Prior to version 117, Google Chrome displayed a lock icon in the address bar, which has since been replaced by a "tune" icon.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Many users believe that a lock icon implies a website is safe, ignoring other security concerns.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The security of HTTPS is that of the underlying TLS, which typically uses long-term public and private keys to generate a short-term session key, which is then used to encrypt the data flow between the client and the server.
[src:hsts-preload/https] X.509 certificates are used to authenticate the server (and sometimes the client as well).
[src:hsts-preload/https] As a consequence, certificate authorities and public key certificates are necessary to verify the relation between the certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:hsts-preload/https] While this can be more beneficial than verifying the identities via a web of trust, the 2013 mass surveillance disclosures drew attention to certificate authorities as a potential weak point allowing man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/https] An important property in this context is forward secrecy, which ensures that encrypted communications recorded in the past cannot be retrieved and decrypted should long-term secret keys or passwords be compromised in the future.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Not all web servers provide forward secrecy.
[src:hsts-preload/https] For HTTPS to be effective, a site must be completely hosted over HTTPS.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Additionally, cookies on a site served through HTTPS must have the secure attribute enabled.
[src:hsts-preload/https] On a site that has sensitive information on it, the user and the session will get exposed every time that site is accessed with HTTP instead of HTTPS.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS URLs begin with "https://" and use port 443 by default, whereas HTTP URLs begin with "http://" and use port 80 by default.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTP is not encrypted and thus is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle and eavesdropping attacks, which can let attackers gain access to website accounts and sensitive information, and modify webpages to inject malware or advertisements.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS is designed to withstand such attacks and is considered secure against them (with the exception of HTTPS implementations that use deprecated versions of SSL).
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTP operates at the highest layer of the TCP/IP model—the application layer; as does the TLS security protocol (operating as a lower sublayer of the same layer), which encrypts an HTTP message prior to transmission and decrypts a message upon arrival.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Strictly speaking, HTTPS is not a separate protocol, but refers to the use of ordinary HTTP over an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS encrypts all message contents, including the HTTP headers and the request/response data.
[src:hsts-preload/https] With the exception of the possible CCA cryptographic attack described in the limitations section below, an attacker should at most be able to discover that a connection is taking place between two parties, along with their domain names and IP addresses.
[src:hsts-preload/https] To prepare a web server to accept HTTPS connections, the administrator must create a public key certificate for the web server.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This certificate must be signed by a trusted certificate authority for the web browser to accept it without warning.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The authority certifies that the certificate holder is the operator of the web server that presents it.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Web browsers are generally distributed with a list of signing certificates of major certificate authorities so that they can verify certificates signed by them.
[src:hsts-preload/https] A number of commercial certificate authorities exist, offering paid-for SSL/TLS certificates of a number of types, including Extended Validation Certificates.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Let's Encrypt, launched in April 2016, provides free and automated service that delivers basic SSL/TLS certificates to websites.
[src:hsts-preload/https] According to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Let's Encrypt will make switching from HTTP to HTTPS "as easy as issuing one command, or clicking one button." The majority of web hosts and cloud providers now leverage Let's Encrypt, providing free certificates to their customers.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The system can also be used for client authentication in order to limit access to a web server to authorized users.
[src:hsts-preload/https] To do this, the site administrator typically creates a certificate for each user, which the user loads into their browser.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Normally, the certificate contains the name and e-mail address of the authorized user and is automatically checked by the server on each connection to verify the user's identity, potentially without even requiring a password.
[src:hsts-preload/https] An important property in this context is perfect forward secrecy (PFS).
[src:hsts-preload/https] Possessing one of the long-term asymmetric secret keys used to establish an HTTPS session should not make it easier to derive the short-term session key to then decrypt the conversation, even at a later time.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Diffie–Hellman key exchange (DHE) and Elliptic-curve Diffie–Hellman key exchange (ECDHE) are in 2013 the only schemes known to have that property.
[src:hsts-preload/https] In 2013, only 30% of Firefox, Opera, and Chromium Browser sessions used it, and nearly 0% of Apple's Safari and Microsoft Internet Explorer sessions.
[src:hsts-preload/https] TLS 1.3, published in August 2018, dropped support for ciphers without forward secrecy.
[src:hsts-preload/https] As of February 2019, 96.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 52.1% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:hsts-preload/https] As of July 2023, 99.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 75.2% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:hsts-preload/https] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, for example because the secrecy of the private key has been compromised.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Newer versions of popular browsers such as Firefox, Opera, and Internet Explorer on Windows Vista implement the Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) to verify that this is not the case.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The browser sends the certificate's serial number to the certificate authority or its delegate via OCSP (Online Certificate Status Protocol) and the authority responds, telling the browser whether the certificate is still valid or not.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The CA may also issue a CRL to tell people that these certificates are revoked.
[src:hsts-preload/https] CRLs are no longer required by the CA/Browser forum, nevertheless, they are still widely used by the CAs.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Most revocation statuses on the Internet disappear soon after the expiration of the certificates.
[src:hsts-preload/https] SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) and TLS (Transport Layer Security) encryption can be configured in two modes: *simple* and *mutual*.
[src:hsts-preload/https] In simple mode, authentication is only performed by the server.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The mutual version requires the user to install a personal client certificate in the web browser for user authentication.
[src:hsts-preload/https] In either case, the level of protection depends on the correctness of the implementation of the software and the cryptographic algorithms in use.
[src:hsts-preload/https] SSL/TLS does not prevent the indexing of the site by a web crawler, and in some cases the URI of the encrypted resource can be inferred by knowing only the intercepted request/response size.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This allows an attacker to have access to the plaintext (the publicly available static content), and the encrypted text (the encrypted version of the static content), permitting a cryptographic attack.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Because TLS operates at a protocol level below that of HTTP and has no knowledge of the higher-level protocols, TLS servers can only strictly present one certificate for a particular address and port combination.
[src:hsts-preload/https] In the past, this meant that it was not feasible to use name-based virtual hosting with HTTPS.
[src:hsts-preload/https] A solution called Server Name Indication (SNI) exists, which sends the hostname to the server before encrypting the connection, although older browsers do not support this extension.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Support for SNI is available since Firefox 2, Opera 8, Apple Safari 2.1, Google Chrome 6, and Internet Explorer 7 on Windows Vista.
[src:hsts-preload/https] A sophisticated type of man-in-the-middle attack called SSL stripping was presented at the 2009 Blackhat Conference.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The attacker then communicates in clear with the client.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This prompted the development of a countermeasure in HTTP called HTTP Strict Transport Security.
[src:hsts-preload/https] HTTPS has been shown to be vulnerable to a range of traffic analysis attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Traffic analysis attacks are a type of side-channel attack that relies on variations in the timing and size of traffic in order to infer properties about the encrypted traffic itself.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Traffic analysis is possible because SSL/TLS encryption changes the contents of traffic, but has minimal impact on the size and timing of traffic.
[src:hsts-preload/https] In May 2010, a research paper by researchers from Microsoft Research and Indiana University discovered that detailed sensitive user data can be inferred from side channels such as packet sizes.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The researchers found that, despite HTTPS protection in several high-profile, top-of-the-line web applications in healthcare, taxation, investment, and web search, an eavesdropper could infer the illnesses/medications/surgeries of the user, his/her family income, and investment secrets.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The fact that most modern websites, including Google, Yahoo!, and Amazon, use HTTPS causes problems for many users trying to access public Wi-Fi hot spots, because a captive portal Wi-Fi hot spot login page fails to load if the user tries to open an HTTPS resource.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Several websites, such as NoSSL.sh, guarantee that they will always remain accessible by HTTP.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Netscape Communications created HTTPS in 1994 for its Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Originally, HTTPS was used with the SSL protocol.
[src:hsts-preload/https] The original SSL protocol was developed by Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications.
[src:hsts-preload/https] As SSL evolved into Transport Layer Security (TLS), HTTPS was formally specified by RFC 2818 in May 2000.
[src:hsts-preload/https] Google announced in February 2018 that its Chrome browser would mark HTTP sites as "Not Secure" after July 2018.
[src:hsts-preload/https] This move was to encourage website owners to implement HTTPS, as an effort to make the World Wide Web more secure.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] In this scenario, the attacker must be able to intercept all relevant messages passing between the two victims and inject new ones.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] This is straightforward in many circumstances; for example, an attacker within range of a Wi-Fi access point hosting a network without encryption could insert themselves as a man in the middle.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] As it aims to circumvent mutual authentication, a MITM attack can succeed only when the attacker impersonates each endpoint sufficiently well to satisfy their expectations.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Most cryptographic protocols include some form of endpoint authentication specifically to prevent MITM attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] For example, TLS can authenticate one or both parties using a mutually trusted certificate authority.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Suppose Alice wishes to communicate with Bob.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Meanwhile, Mallory wishes to intercept the conversation to eavesdrop (breaking confidentiality) with the option to deliver a false message to Bob under the guise of Alice (breaking non-repudiation).
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Mallory would perform a man-in-the-middle attack as described in the following sequence of events.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Mallory relays this message to Bob; Bob cannot tell it is not really from Alice: Alice Mallory *"Hi Bob, it's Alice.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Bob thinks that this message is a secure communication from Alice.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] This example shows the need for Alice and Bob to have a means to ensure that they are truly each using each other's public keys, and not the public key of an attacker.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Otherwise, such attacks are generally possible, in principle, against any message sent using public-key technology.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] There are several attack types that can fall into the category of MITM.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] SSL/TLS stripping: Downgrades HTTPS traffic to HTTP, intercepting and reading unencrypted data.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] ARP spoofing: Sends fake ARP messages to associate the attacker’s MAC address with a target IP, intercepting local network traffic.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] DNS spoofing or poisoning: Redirects DNS queries to malicious servers, leading victims to fake websites.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Session hijacking: Steals session cookies or tokens to impersonate a legitimate user in an active session.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Man-in-the-browser (MITB): Malware alters browser activity, intercepting or manipulating transactions in real-time.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Wi-Fi MITM (evil twin attack): Creates a fake Wi-Fi hotspot to intercept communications from connected devices.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Email hijacking: Intercepts email exchanges to manipulate or steal sensitive information.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Replay attacks: Captures and retransmits valid data to repeat actions or disrupt communication.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Fake certificate authority (CA): Uses a fraudulent CA to sign fake certificates, tricking victims into trusting malicious connections.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] MITM attacks can be prevented or detected by two means: authentication and tamper detection.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Authentication provides some degree of certainty that a given message has come from a legitimate source.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Tamper detection merely shows evidence that a message may have been altered and has broken integrity.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] All cryptographic systems that are secure against MITM attacks provide some method of authentication for messages.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Most require an exchange of information (such as public keys) in addition to the message over a secure channel.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Such protocols, often using key-agreement protocols, have been developed with different security requirements for the secure channel, though some have attempted to remove the requirement for any secure channel at all.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] A public key infrastructure, such as Transport Layer Security, may harden Transmission Control Protocol against MITM attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] In such structures, clients and servers exchange certificates which are issued and verified by a trusted third party called a certificate authority (CA).
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] If the original key to authenticate this CA has not been itself the subject of a MITM attack, then the certificates issued by the CA may be used to authenticate the messages sent by the owner of that certificate.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Use of mutual authentication, in which both the server and the client validate the other's communication, covers both ends of a MITM attack.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] If the server or client's identity is not verified or deemed as invalid, the session will end.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] However, the default behavior of most connections is to only authenticate the server, which means mutual authentication is not always employed and MITM attacks can still occur.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Attestments, such as verbal communications of a shared value (as in ZRTP), or recorded attestments such as audio/visual recordings of a public key hash are used to ward off MITM attacks, as visual media is much more difficult and time-consuming to imitate than simple data packet communication.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] However, these methods require a human in the loop in order to successfully initiate the transaction.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] While HTTP Public Key Pinning (HPKP) was originally designed to prevent MITM attacks involving compromised certificate authorities, it has been deprecated by major browsers due to its high risk of accidental site bricking.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] It has been widely superseded by Certificate Transparency (CT), which mandates that all TLS certificates be logged in publicly auditable records to detect fraudulent or unauthorized certificates in real time.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] DNSSEC extends the DNS protocol to use signatures to authenticate DNS records, preventing simple MITM attacks from directing a client to a malicious IP address.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Latency examination can potentially detect the attack in certain situations, such as with long calculations that lead into tens of seconds like hash functions.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] To detect potential attacks, parties check for discrepancies in response times.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] For example: Say that two parties normally take a certain amount of time to perform a particular transaction.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] If one transaction, however, were to take an abnormal length of time to reach the other party, this could be indicative of a third party's presence interfering with the connection and inserting additional latency in the transaction.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Quantum cryptography, in theory, provides tamper-evidence for transactions through the no-cloning theorem.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Protocols based on quantum cryptography typically authenticate part or all of their classical communication with an unconditionally secure authentication scheme.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] As an example Wegman-Carter authentication.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Captured network traffic from what is suspected to be an attack can be analyzed in order to determine whether there was an attack and, if so, determine the source of the attack.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] A Stingray phone tracker is a cellular phone surveillance device that mimics a wireless carrier cell tower in order to force all nearby mobile phones and other cellular data devices to connect to it.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] The tracker relays all communications back and forth between cellular phones and cell towers.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] In 2011, a security breach of the Dutch certificate authority DigiNotar resulted in the fraudulent issuing of certificates.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Subsequently, the fraudulent certificates were used to perform MITM attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] In 2013, Nokia's Xpress Browser was revealed to be decrypting HTTPS traffic on Nokia's proxy servers, giving the company clear text access to its customers' encrypted browser traffic.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Nokia responded by saying that the content was not stored permanently, and that the company had organizational and technical measures to prevent access to private information.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] In 2017, Equifax withdrew its mobile phone apps following concern about MITM vulnerabilities.
[src:hsts-preload/man-in-the-middle-attack] Bluetooth, a wireless communication protocol, has also been susceptible to man-in-the-middle attacks due to its wireless transmission of data.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike is a former head of the security team at Twitter and the author of a proposed SSL authentication system replacement called Convergence.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] He previously maintained a cloud-based WPA cracking service and a targeted anonymity service called GoogleSharing.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike began his career working for several technology companies, including enterprise infrastructure software maker BEA Systems Inc.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In 2010, Marlinspike was the chief technology officer and co-founder of Whisper Systems, an enterprise mobile security startup company.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In May 2010, Whisper Systems launched TextSecure and RedPhone.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] These were applications that provided end-to-end encrypted SMS messaging and voice calling, respectively.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Twitter acquired the company for an undisclosed amount in late 2011.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] The acquisition was done "primarily so that Mr.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike could help the then-startup improve its security".
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] During his time as Twitter's head of cybersecurity, the firm made Whisper Systems' apps open source.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike left Twitter in early 2013 and founded Open Whisper Systems as a collaborative open source project for the continued development of TextSecure and RedPhone.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] At the time, Marlinspike and Trevor Perrin started developing the Signal Protocol, an early version of which was first introduced in the TextSecure app in February 2014.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In November 2015, Open Whisper Systems unified the TextSecure and RedPhone applications as Signal.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Between 2014 and 2016, Marlinspike worked with WhatsApp, Facebook, and Google to integrate the Signal Protocol into their messaging services.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In 2017, Marlinspike assisted the cryptocurrency company MobileCoin as an early technical advisors alongside fellow former DARPA researcher Todd Huffman.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] MobileCoin was designed to be the in-app payments for Signal and Mixin Messenger.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] On February 21, 2018, Marlinspike and WhatsApp co-founder Brian Acton announced the formation of the Signal Technology Foundation and its subsidiary, Signal Messenger LLC.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike served as Signal Messenger's first CEO until stepping down on January 10, 2022.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In the wake of the United States government group chat leak Marlinspike posted in March 2025: "There are so many great reasons to be on Signal.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Now including the opportunity for the vice president of the United States of America to randomly add you to a group chat for coordinating sensitive military operations.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In a 2009 paper, Marlinspike introduced the concept of SSL stripping, a man-in-the-middle attack in which a network attacker could prevent a web browser from upgrading to an SSL connection in a way that would likely go unnoticed by a user.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] He also announced the release of a tool, `sslstrip`, that would automatically perform these types of man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] The HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) specification was subsequently developed to combat these attacks.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike has discovered a number of different vulnerabilities in popular SSL implementations.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Notably, he published a 2002 paper on exploiting SSL/TLS implementations that did not correctly verify the X.509 v3 "BasicConstraints" extension in public key certificate chains.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] This allowed anyone with a valid CA-signed certificate for any domain name to create what appeared to be valid CA-signed certificates for any other domain.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] The vulnerable SSL/TLS implementations included the Microsoft CryptoAPI, making Internet Explorer and all other Windows software that relied on SSL/TLS connections vulnerable to a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In 2011, the same vulnerability was discovered to have remained in the SSL/TLS implementation on Apple Inc.'s iOS.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Also notably, Marlinspike presented a 2009 paper in which he introduced the concept of a null-prefix attack on SSL certificates.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] He revealed that all major SSL implementations failed to properly verify the Common Name value of a certificate, so that they could be tricked into accepting forged certificates by embedding null characters into the CN field.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In 2011, Marlinspike presented a talk, "SSL And The Future Of Authenticity", at the Black Hat security conference in Las Vegas.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] He outlined many of the problems with certificate authorities and announced the release of a software project called Convergence to replace them.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In 2012, Marlinspike and Perrin submitted an Internet Draft for TACK, which is designed to provide SSL certificate pinning and help solve the CA problem, to the Internet Engineering Task Force.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In 2012, Marlinspike and David Hulton presented research that makes it possible to reduce the security of MS-CHAPv2 handshakes to a single DES encryption.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Hulton built hardware capable of cracking the remaining DES encryption in less than 24 hours, and the two made the hardware available for anyone to use as an Internet service.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In 2013, Marlinspike published emails on his blog that he claimed were from Saudi Arabian telecom service Mobily soliciting his help in surveilling their customers, including intercepting communications running through various applications.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike refused to help, making the emails public instead.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] "We never communicate with hackers", the company said.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike says that when flying within the United States he is unable to print his own boarding pass, is required to have airline ticketing agents make a phone call in order to issue one, and is subjected to secondary screening at TSA security checkpoints.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] While entering the U.S. on a flight from the Dominican Republic in 2010, Marlinspike was detained by federal agents for nearly five hours, all his electronic devices were confiscated, and at first agents claimed he would only get them back if he provided his passwords so they could decrypt the data.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Originally from the state of Georgia, Marlinspike moved to San Francisco in the late 1990s at age 18.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] The name *Moxie Marlinspike* is an assumed name partly derived from a childhood nickname.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] Marlinspike is a sailing enthusiast and master mariner.
[src:hsts-preload/moxie-marlinspike] In 2004, he bought a derelict sailboat and, with three friends, refurbished it and sailed around the Bahamas while making a "video zine" about their journey called *Hold Fast*.
